        "MAN_0011",
        "MAN_0290",
        "/Users/rhea.chatterjeeyale.edu/rag-audio/audio/de-identified_transcripts/PMHCycle3-de-Identified/PMHCycle3-9.23.19-de_identified/MVI_0244.txt",
        "/Users/rhea.chatterjeeyale.edu/rag-audio/audio/de-identified_transcripts/PMHCycle3-de-Identified/PMHCycle3-9.23.19-de_identified/MVI_0244.txt",
        "/Users/rhea.chatterjeeyale.edu/rag-audio/audio/de-identified_transcripts/PMHCycle3-de-Identified/PMHCycle3-9.23.19-de_identified/MVI_0244.txt"
      ],
      "answer_text": "Participants put mindful\u2011eating skills into practice by first learning to notice and label their internal signals\u2014such as the seven types of hunger and cravings\u2014and then using that awareness to pause before making food choices.  In sessions they complete a \"Choices\" exercise that guides them to examine the options on the plate, consider how each choice aligns with their hunger, health goals, and values, and select the healthier alternative.  They reinforce these skills with a mindfulness\u2011attitudes checklist (e.g., non\u2011judgment, curiosity) and track their experiences in a food\u2011journal or activity\u2011log, which helps them identify patterns and adjust behavior.  Goal\u2011setting sheets and quick\u2011reference handouts further support the translation of mindful awareness into concrete nutrition goals, leading to more balanced, health\u2011conscious eating."
    },
